  "prompt": "Are there legal obligations for financial institutions regarding money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, financial institutions have significant legal obligations to prevent money laundering. These typically include:\n\n1. Customer Due Diligence (CDD)\n- Verifying customer identities\n- Screening customers against watchlists\n- Understanding source of customer funds\n\n2. Reporting Requirements\n- Filing Suspicious Activity Reports (SARs)\n- Reporting cash transactions above certain thresholds\n- Maintaining detailed transaction records\n\n3. Compliance Programs\n- Establishing internal anti-money laundering (AML) policies\n- Conducting regular staff training\n- Implementing robust monitoring systems\n\n4. Risk Assessment\n- Identifying high-risk customers/transactions\n- Conducting enhanced due diligence for potentially suspicious activities\n\n5. Know Your Customer (KYC) Regulations\n- Collecting comprehensive customer information\n- Performing ongoing customer risk assessments\n\n6. International Compliance\n- Following guidelines from organizations like FATF\n- Adhering to international anti-money laundering standards\n\n7. Potential Penalties\n- Significant financial fines\n- Potential criminal liability\n- Loss of operating licenses\n\nThese obligations are designed to prevent financial crimes and protect the global financial system's integrity.",
